<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The Problem With Tom<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.46)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9038'>Jared "Mister" Stein</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9038&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 21, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> The Problem With Tom<br>
or <br>
Why Tom Bombadil Should Never Be a Character Card<br>
<br>
 * * *<br>
<br>
Tom Bombadil - Master<br>
Twilight Cost: 0<br>
Ally<br>
Home: Site 2<br>
Strength: 8 [infinite]<br>
Vitality: 8 [infinite]<br>
Text: Tom may not carry possessions. Manuever: If all companions are exhausted Tom Bombadil is Defender + 3 and may participate in Archery and Skirmish phases.<br>
Flavor Text: &quot;He Has no fear. Tom Bombadil is Master.&quot;<br>
<br>
 * * *<br>
<br>
To put it bluntly: I hate fantasy cards for ccgs.  They bore me.  I don&#39;t like making them and I don&#39;t like reading them.  But here I have made a fantasy card for Tom Bombadil. Why? To exemplify a point: Tom Bombadil should not be a playable card in The Lord of the Rings TCG.  There are many problems with the idea of a Tom Bombadil card but it really comes down to two observations based on a close reading of The Lord of the Rings and The Silmarillion: a textually accurate Tom Bombadil would be overly powerful, thus a &quot;broken&quot; card; a playable, non-broken Tom Bombadil card would be inaccurate to the text (underpowered).<br>
<br>
Who Is Tom Bombadil?<br>
The question that is never fully answerable! When Sam asks Goldberry she simply replies in the most cryptic of ways, &quot;He is.&quot;  In literary history the only other character referred to in so simple yet so complete a manner is the god of the Old and New Testaments.  Some scholars have suggested that Tom Bombadil is in fact God--Iluvater, the god of Middle Earth as described in the Simarillion.  The textual evidence for this claim is strong throughout LOTR.  At the very least it seems clear that Tom is immortal, not as the elves are immortal but as one outside and apart from the world is immortal. And his strength is immeasurable. With a song he subdues the will of Old Man Willow, perhaps the strongest and oldest living thing on the planet.  He can be anywhere at any moment, can hear a hobbit&#39;s song miles away, and sees even that which is hidden by the One Ring.<br>
<br>
Speaking of the One Ring Tom Bombadil is the single character that is not only unaffected by it, but even disregards the Ring as being somehow worthless. To what sort of person would the One Ring, the Ring of Power, the ring that can be used to conquer the whole of Middle Earth be unimportant? Only to one who&#39;s own power far exceeds that offered by the Ring.  With this conclusion and the evidence listed above we can suggest that Tom Bombadil&#39;s strength and vitality numbers would be comparably through the roof.  In my fantasy card (above) I sided with the Bombadil-god theory and made them infinite since I could not realistically imagine a number (though I might have just listed them both as 99).  Tom was the first to arrive and will be the last to leave.  His strength does not fail or does his will falter; neither has he failed nor faltered through all the ages of elves and men.  To be accurate to the text one has to concede that a Tom Bombadil card would full of power and vitality. <br>
<br>
Tom Bombadil, The Card<br>
How could one translate Tom&#39;s cryptic powers (or as I would suggest, his pure Power) into a ccg card?  We&#39;ve seen no character like him in any other ccg before now; only Yoda in SWCCG comes close for, as I have tried to prove, Tom Bombadil is first and foremost an unbelievably powerful character. This alone should make him a &quot;broken&quot; card by nature.  But let&#39;s move past that for now. It seems clear from the start that, were Decipher to make a character card of him, Tom would be a Free People&#39;s card as he has no observable interest in the Ring, let alone in returning it to Sauron. Assigning Tom to a Free Peoples culture is a little bit tricky, but assuming that he is in some way connected to Iluvater (if he is not in fact an incarnation of Iluvater) we can attach him to the Wizard culture.  Though somewhat inaccurate, there is a relationship between Gandalf (an angel-like character called an Istari) and Tom Bombadil that is visible in the final book of The Lord of the Rings.<br>
<br>
So we&#39;ve got him as a Free Peoples Wizard culture card.  Now let me suggest that Tom is more likely to be an Ally card rather than a Companion.  Why not a companion? Because he does not care enough about the fate of the Ring enough to join. The council of Elrond dismisses the idea of giving the Ring to Tom because he would just forget about it.  Though this may be simply another reason not to include him in the game, there is something that he does seem to care about: the fate of the Fellowship and the safety of the hobbits in particular. If Tom is to be an Ally I argue that he must be one, like Thrarin, that can be brought into battle to save the Fellowship of the Ring.  And yet to exert Tom like Thrarin would be silly, as he seems to be impervious and immortal.  Rather than exert him I tried to make my fantasy card _somewhat_ reasonable by following the text of the book: Tom can participate only when the party most desperately needs it, when all companions are exhausted.  He is made defender +3 so he can cover all the hobbits.  Though the conditions for bringing Tom into battle are rare to be sure, could it be exploited, making Tom an even more broken card? Absolutely. And that&#39;s another reason why Tom should not be a card.<br>
<br>
But we all want Tom. Tom is cool. Tom is mysterious. Tom is god. OK, that last claim is debatable. But he is one of the most intriguiging and popular characters in the book.  So how could Decipher make a Tom Bombadil card that was not broken? If they do make a character card of Tom he would have to be an Ally, but one that could not particpate in archery and skirmish phases outside of his home site for the simple fact that he seems to be omnipotent.  Better yet: let no skirmishes occur at Tom&#39;s home while he is there.  Yet some would argue that this restriction goes against the text of the novel, as Tom clearly leaves his home to famously rescue the hobbits from the barrow wights, and we get the sense that Tom would have flown to Mordor if only he had been called upon.  If such a Tom card was created I can imagine balance in the form of counter cards for the Shadow side; for example, an event called &quot;Goodberry Is Waiting&quot; that prevents Tom from participating in any phases of battle in a single turn. <br>
<br>
The real decision for the Tom Bombadil card(s) will come from Decipher, if not with the future installments of Lord of the Rings then definitely with post-&quot;trilogy&quot; expansions such as the unavoidable Lord of the Rings Reflections I, II, & III.  What I would hope is that either Tom not be taken lightly, that a Tom Bombadil card be primarily accurate to the text; if that makes him broken then he should not be in the game at all. A much simpler solution would be not to create a Tom Bombadil character card but rather to create unique event cards that would refer to Tom, such as &quot;Tom Bombadil&#39;s Nonsense Song&quot; which could do something like this:  Spot 4 or more exhausted companions to cancel all remaining skirmishes. A powerful card, but one worthy of Tom&#39;s mystery and grandeur.<br>
